                <!-- The Complexity Trap -->
                <div class="animate-on-scroll lg:flex lg:gap-12 lg:items-start">
                    <div class="lg:w-1/3 mb-4 lg:mb-0">
                        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            <h3 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-4xl tracking-tight text-sf-red">What is the Complexity Trap?</h3>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="lg:w-2/3">
                        <blockquote class="text-lg md:text-xl text-gray-300 leading-relaxed border-l-2 border-sf-red pl-6">
                            The Complexity Trap is a self-reinforcing cycle where teams add layers, abstractions, services, and tools in the name of flexibility, scalability, or modernity &mdash; and end up with systems nobody fully understands or can safely change. Each addition seems reasonable in isolation. A new abstraction layer here. A message queue there. A microservice to handle that one thing that might need to scale independently someday. And then, six months later, nobody can ship a feature without touching seven repositories, consulting three different teams, and running a deployment pipeline that takes longer than the actual code change.
                        </blockquote>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <hr class="border-sf-border" />

                <!-- The Core Insight -->
                <div class="animate-on-scroll lg:flex lg:gap-12 lg:items-start">
                    <div class="lg:w-1/3 mb-4 lg:mb-0">
                        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            <h3 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-4xl tracking-tight text-sf-red">The Core Insight</h3>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="lg:w-2/3">
                        <blockquote class="text-lg md:text-xl text-gray-300 leading-relaxed border-l-2 border-sf-red pl-6">
                            Complexity isn't a sign of incompetence. It's frequently a sign of intelligence applied without the right constraints. The smartest engineers share a common trait: they're suspicious of complexity. They treat every new dependency as a cost to be justified, not a feature to be celebrated.
                        </blockquote>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <hr class="border-sf-border" />

                <!-- What Simplicity-First Means -->
                <div class="animate-on-scroll lg:flex lg:gap-12 lg:items-start">
                    <div class="lg:w-1/3 mb-4 lg:mb-0">
                        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            <h3 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-4xl tracking-tight text-sf-red">What Simplicity-First Means</h3>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="lg:w-2/3">
                        <blockquote class="text-lg md:text-xl text-gray-300 leading-relaxed border-l-2 border-sf-red pl-6">
                            Simplicity-First means starting simple, evolving incrementally, and adding complexity only when it demonstrably pays for itself. It means keeping architecture aligned with real needs by focusing on actual requirements rather than hypothetical scenarios. Every component earns its place. Every abstraction pays for itself. Every dependency gets justified.
                        </blockquote>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <hr class="border-sf-border" />

                <!-- The Operational Definition -->
                <div class="animate-on-scroll lg:flex lg:gap-12 lg:items-start">
                    <div class="lg:w-1/3 mb-4 lg:mb-0">
                        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            <h3 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-4xl tracking-tight text-sf-red">The Operational Definition</h3>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="lg:w-2/3">
                        <blockquote class="text-lg md:text-xl text-gray-300 leading-relaxed border-l-2 border-sf-red pl-6">
                            A system is simple if a tired, stressed, unfamiliar engineer can understand it well enough to fix it quickly. This definition has teeth. It does not care about elegant abstractions or clever patterns. It cares about one thing: can this system be operated under stress by normal humans?
                        </blockquote>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

