                        <div class="w-12 h-12 mb-6 text-sf-red">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" class="w-12 h-12" aria-hidden="true">
                                <path d="M12 2a10 10 0 0 1 0 20" />
                                <line x1="12" y1="2" x2="12" y2="22" stroke-dasharray="2 2" />
                            </svg>
                        </div>
                        <h3 class="font-display text-3xl tracking-tight mb-3">The Half-Rule</h3>
                        <p class="text-sf-red font-mono text-sm mb-4">Are we building only what we know we need?</p>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
                            Build half of what you think you need. Treat the rest as a hypothesis to be tested, not a requirement to be fulfilled. Every team has a complexity budget &mdash; a real constraint on what your organization can handle. When teams overbuild early, they spend that budget on imaginary problems. The Half-Rule protects your budget for problems you know are real.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Filter 3: Primary Path First -->
                <div class="card-hover bg-sf-black border border-sf-border rounded-sm p-8 animate-on-scroll stagger-3">
                    <div class="border-t-2 border-sf-red -mt-8 pt-8 -mx-8 px-8">
